_⚠️ Potential issue_ | _🟠 Major_

**Race condition in rate limiting allows concurrent scans.**

The lock is released after the rate-limit check (line 76) but before the timestamp is updated (line 83). This creates a TOCTOU vulnerability where multiple concurrent requests can pass the rate-limit check before any of them updates `_lastScanTime`, allowing multiple expensive `CalculateStatistics()` calls to run simultaneously.



<details>
<summary>🔒 Proposed fix: Set timestamp immediately after passing check</summary>

```diff
     [HttpGet("ScanLibraries")]
     [ProducesResponseType(StatusCodes.Status200OK)]
     [ProducesResponseType(StatusCodes.Status429TooManyRequests)]
     public ActionResult<MediaStatisticsResult> ScanLibraries()
     {
         lock (RateLimitLock)
         {
             var now = DateTime.UtcNow;
             if (now - _lastScanTime < MinScanInterval)
             {
                 PluginLogService.LogWarning("API", "Rate limit exceeded for statistics scan", logger: _logger);
                 return StatusCode(StatusCodes.Status429TooManyRequests, new { message = "Please wait before requesting another scan." });
             }
+
+            // Set timestamp immediately to prevent concurrent scans
+            SetLastScanTime(now);
         }

         var result = _statisticsService.CalculateStatistics();

-        // Set rate-limit timestamp AFTER the scan so a failed scan does not block retries for 30s
-        lock (RateLimitLock)
-        {
-            SetLastScanTime(DateTime.UtcNow);
-        }
-
         _cache.Set(StatsCacheKey, result, CacheDuration);
         _cacheService.SaveLatestResult(result);

         return Ok(result);
     }
```

</details>

**Note:** This changes behavior so a failed scan will block retries for 30 seconds. If preserving the "failed scan doesn't block" behavior is important, consider using a `SemaphoreSlim(1, 1)` instead to ensure only one scan runs at a time while still allowing retries after failures.

<!-- suggestion_start -->

<details>
<summary>📝 Committable suggestion</summary>

> ‼️ **IMPORTANT**
> Carefully review the code before committing. Ensure that it accurately replaces the highlighted code, contains no missing lines, and has no issues with indentation. Thoroughly test & benchmark the code to ensure it meets the requirements.

```suggestion
        [HttpGet("ScanLibraries")]
        [ProducesResponseType(StatusCodes.Status200OK)]
        [ProducesResponseType(StatusCodes.Status429TooManyRequests)]
        public ActionResult<MediaStatisticsResult> ScanLibraries()
        {
            lock (RateLimitLock)
            {
                var now = DateTime.UtcNow;
                if (now - _lastScanTime < MinScanInterval)
                {
                    PluginLogService.LogWarning("API", "Rate limit exceeded for statistics scan", logger: _logger);
                    return StatusCode(StatusCodes.Status429TooManyRequests, new { message = "Please wait before requesting another scan." });
                }

                // Set timestamp immediately to prevent concurrent scans
                SetLastScanTime(now);
            }

            var result = _statisticsService.CalculateStatistics();

            _cache.Set(StatsCacheKey, result, CacheDuration);
            _cacheService.SaveLatestResult(result);

            return Ok(result);
        }
```

</details>

<!-- suggestion_end -->

<details>
<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>

```
Verify each finding against the current code and only fix it if needed.

In `@Jellyfin.Plugin.JellyfinHelper/Api/MediaStatisticsController.cs` around lines
68 - 84, The rate-limit lock currently only guards the check but not the
timestamp update, allowing a TOCTOU race where multiple requests can pass the
check and call _statisticsService.CalculateStatistics(); fix by acquiring
RateLimitLock, check (now - _lastScanTime < MinScanInterval), and if allowed
immediately call SetLastScanTime(DateTime.UtcNow) while still under the same
lock before releasing it, then call _statisticsService.CalculateStatistics();
alternatively, if you must avoid blocking retries on failed scans, replace the
lock logic with a SemaphoreSlim(1,1) around the CalculateStatistics() call to
serialize scans without setting _lastScanTime on failure.
```

</details>

